03932nam a22005055i 9780773582101DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20032003xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735821017 a10.1515/97807735821012doi  a(DE-B1597)657079  a(OCoLC)767671267  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJC571 ǂb G67 2003eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a323.011 aGorman, Jonathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRights and Reason :bAn Introduction to the Philosophy of Rights /cJonathan Gorman. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (241 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPlato -- tHobbes -- tLocke -- tHuman Motivation -- tHuman Value -- tHohfeld’S Analysis -- tHohfeld’S Analysis Analysed -- tChange -- tInconsistency -- tUnderstanding Rights -- tThe Rights-Based Approach -- tDuty and Justice -- tConclusion -- tUnited Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights -- tCouncil of Europe Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms, as amended by Protocol No. 11 Rome, 4.XI.1950 -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHe begins by contrasting the ideas of Plato, Hobbes, and Locke and their appeal to reason with the empiricism of Hume, showing that the issue of whether rights can express independent authoritative standards is inseparable from the longstanding conflict between empiricism and rationalism. By examining Kant's attempt to resolve this conflict he shows that Kant changed our understanding of morality, and of rights in particular, by basing his philosophy on an analysis of human language. An outline of Hohfeld's analysis of the language of rights and duties completes the examination of rights and reason. Gorman goes on to investigate some substantive criteria for the application of concepts of rights, including the beneficiary view of a right, group rights, non-human rights, the nature of the "individuals" who are the bearers of rights, the "interest" theory of rights, and the "will" theory. Finally he examines the view that rights and duties are mutually supporting features of a just situation, introducing Rawl's theory of justice. Throughout Gorman shows that, alongside arguments about the content of rights and the myriad claims to rights, there are pluralities of theories that offer some understanding of the moral and legal realm and of the places that rights may hold in it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358210140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773582101423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773582101/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles